      <p>Finally, to get a sense of each method's accuracy, we evaluated the tables of DERs between sexes and between males produced by each method. We gathered all resulting regionsâboth negative results, from the male vs. male comparison, and positive results, from the male vs. female comparisonâand ordered them by the value of their test statistic. An algorithm ranking all positive results ahead of the negative ones is preferred. Fig. <xref ref-type="fig" rid="KXT053F4">4</xref> shows, at each percentile of the differential expression test statistic, the percent of regions that are positive. This is analogous to finding the percentage of findings that were truly positive at different significance cutoffs, assuming all tests in the sex comparison should be positives and tests in the male comparison should be negatives. We find that EdgeR, DESeq, and DER Finder perform comparably: all or most of the top 20% of regions, ranked by test statistic, came from comparisons between sexes. Cufflinks does much worse: only about 60% of the top 20% of their top transcripts came from the male-to-female comparison. DER Finder performs just slightly better than EdgeR and DESeq in addition to having other advantages over these methods, as discussed earlier.
